Box vs violin plots¶

The following I copied from Wiki
A box plot or boxplot is a method for graphically depicting groups of numerical data through their quartiles. Box plots may also have lines extending vertically from the boxes (whiskers) indicating variability outside the upper and lower quartiles, hence the terms box-and-whisker plot and box-and-whisker diagram. Outliers may be plotted as individual points.

A violin plot is a method of plotting numeric data. It is similar to a box plot with a rotated kernel density plot on each side.

In [119]:
sns.boxplot(data=df[['Age']]);

Change orientation

In [115]:
sns.boxplot(x='Age', data=df[['Age']]);

Violinplot draws a combination of boxplot and kernel density estimate.

In [120]:
sns.kdeplot(data=df['Age'], shade=True);
In [121]:
sns.violinplot(x='Age', data=df[['Age']]);

Scatter plot with the distributions of variables

sns.jointplot(data=df, x='Age', y='Fare');

Regression plot within jointplot¶

You can call just regplot()

In [183]:
f, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(8, 8))
sns.regplot(data=df, x='SALE\nPRICE', y='GROSS SQUARE FEET');
Out[183]:
<matplotlib.axes._subplots.AxesSubplot at 0x2178ce46c50>

But try to understand the anatomy of jointplot()

In [184]:
jnt = sns.jointplot(x='SALE\nPRICE', y='GROSS SQUARE FEET', data=df, height=8);

There are three subplots (axes-objects) within jointplot:

Do the following:

  • Filter outliers by 0.5e8 for x and by 6e5 for y
  • Plot regression line onto scatterplot (pass certain parameter to jointplot)
  • Disable tick labels of both X&Y distplots to hide "1e8" (get x axis from x distplot (marginal plot) and use set_visible())
  • Low case both labels of scatterplot axis X&Y (e.g. 'GROSS' -> 'Gross')
  • Pad label of scatterplot axis Y

In [284]:
from math import log10
from matplotlib.ticker import FuncFormatter

def fun(x,pos):
    if x == 0: return "$0$"
    if x > 0:
        x = int(x)
        pow = int(log10(x))
        man = int(x // 10 ** pow)
        return r"${} \times 10^{}$".format(man,pow)
In [286]:
jnt.ax_joint.yaxis.set_major_formatter(FuncFormatter(fun))
